  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "No — one note at line 25 is sufficient; front-loading would steal the conceptual birth moment",
    "content": "**No. One note at line 25 is sufficient.**\n\nBrief reasoning: At line 17, the reader has not yet encountered *Jing* as a technical concept. Telling them that 境界 = \"boundary of *Jing*\" at this point gives them information they cannot use --- *Jing* means nothing to them yet. The note would be noise, or worse, it would prime the reader to think 境界 IS the key concept, when in fact 境界 is the shell that 境 will break out of.\n\nThe power of line 25 is precisely that it is the moment where the reader already has 境界 = \"bounds\" established from lines 17 and 19, and then sees bare 境 appear for the first time. The footnote at line 25 can do both jobs at once: note the etymology AND mark the conceptual birth. Front-loading at line 17 would steal that moment's force.\n\nLet the reader encounter 境界 as simply \"bounds\" at line 17, encounter it again at line 19, develop a feel for it as \"the limits of thought/language,\" and then experience the separation at line 25. This is itself a load-bearing sequence."
  }
}
